<div id="review_343932705" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/343932705" />
    <a title="Gerry" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3559010-gerry"><img alt="Gerry" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/343932705?book_show_action=true">Jun 07, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gerry" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gerry" href="/user/show/3559010-gerry">Gerry</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3559010-gerry?shelf=reviews">reviews</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer343932705" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14664987856309071100"><br/> <br/><br/>Anyone choosing to read a novel pitting Pro-Life against Pro-Choice should be prepared for an emotional thumping, even if the author skillfully avoids taking sides, as is the case here. However, Equity of Evil goes beyond the volatile abortion topic, into the dark black-market world of human organ trafficking and murder in an international setting. This is no imagined tale, but one supported by facts. Nor is the growing of human organs all that different from hydroponic farming. Throw in intern</span>
  <span id="freeText14664987856309071100" style="display:none"><br /> <br /><br />Anyone choosing to read a novel pitting Pro-Life against Pro-Choice should be prepared for an emotional thumping, even if the author skillfully avoids taking sides, as is the case here. However, Equity of Evil goes beyond the volatile abortion topic, into the dark black-market world of human organ trafficking and murder in an international setting. This is no imagined tale, but one supported by facts. Nor is the growing of human organs all that different from hydroponic farming. Throw in international intrigue, conspiracy, duplicity, megalomania, risk mania and human torment, and you have the ingredients of not just one, but several novels.<br /> <br />One of the marvelous aspects of this medical thriller is rooted in the verifiable medical background of the author, who writes as though he has been there in more than a few ways. The characters are so well developed that no physical descriptions are necessary— their actions and words define them. Indeed, I believe I have met Roman Citrano, Dr. Marcus Levine and Andrea Robbins several times in my life, each with different names and at different times, in other circumstances. Scenes in the novel are easily visualized, dialogue well done, and the story line moves without letup until the final page. <br /><br />The novel delivers a reasonable ending, given the volatile nature of the major premise, but a truly satisfactory ending may have been impossible. Those at the top are still there, unseen, wielding their puppet strings, and the billion-dollar illicit enterprise will continue.<br /><br />Which makes me wonder about a possible sequel. If this is indeed the author’s first-ever novel, the reading public is in for some future treats. I’ll be watching for the next one.<br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13435349.Equity_of_Evil" title="Equity of Evil by Rudy Mazzocchi" rel="nofollow noopener">Equity of Evil</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="14664987856309071100" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


